This paper is about the Open Annotation Core Data Model, which is a framework for creating associations between related resources. The paper discusses the technical decisions that were made in designing the model, and provides use cases to motivate interoperable annotations. 

Based on this information, the most likely sub-category is cs.CY (Computers and Society), as the paper discusses the implications of the Open Annotation model for sharing information and collaborating across platforms. 

The paper also touches on issues related to digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), and databases (cs.DB), as these are all areas where annotations can be useful for organizing and accessing information. 

Finally, the paper discusses the user interface implications of the Open Annotation model, which could fall under the sub-category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
